01:09.581 --> 01:13.966
and I was there for a year. Let me ask you this. Back 
in those days, was the state veterinarian really a

01:18.532 --> 01:25.440
state veterinarian back then or not?

01:26.982 --> 01:28.324
They had... They had a

01:29.620 --> 01:40.412
lot of authority and a lot of power.

01:43.075 --> 01:57.791
In fact,

01:43.075 --> 01:57.791
I used my power in reverse in many instances where I 
didn't think it was necessary to quarantine a herd

01:43.075 --> 01:57.791
or take some kind of action. Well, I helped Yeah, 
for instance,

01:59.422 --> 02:12.493
in

01:59.422 --> 02:12.493
the fall of 45, there were some Brahma Bulls. You 
may know about this. The Mexicans down there on the

02:14.856 --> 02:20.741
border, what were their names? The Garas? What? 
The Garas. Garas. Garas, that's the one. They

02:26.646 --> 02:27.927
brought those... those red bremas in from Brazil. 
Now, when they left Brazil, they were Brazilian

02:33.476 --> 02:37.962
bulls. They got into Mexico, they were Mexican 
bulls. They came across the border into Texas.

02:44.610 --> 02:47.894
When they got over here, they reverted back to 
Brazilian bulls. Well, we needed that blood. We

02:51.158 --> 02:55.703
needed that blood, you know.

02:57.809 --> 02:58.690
We didn't know about it. We didn't know about it 
until the following April. In April of 46, Francis

03:02.115 --> 03:15.433
and I were in Hermosillo, Mexico, at a U.S. and 
Mexico sanitary meeting. And somebody told me

03:15.454 --> 03:19.840
that we had some Brazilian bulls in Texas. What are 
you going to do about it? I says, I don't know until I

03:21.462 --> 03:22.764
get home. I came home. Those bulls had been in 
contact with those highly susceptible cattle

03:26.868 --> 03:38.139
from here for six months. I said, what are you going 
to do with these bulls? They said, we're not going

03:42.042 --> 03:43.604
to do anything with them. We're going to keep them 
right here. I says, if you'll keep those bulls

03:44.825 --> 03:53.533
right here, we're going to have somebody examine 
them every 30 days, and if anything goes wrong that

03:54.003 --> 04:00.914
if you have any sickness or it looks like you might 
have some trouble, you contact me and we'll be glad

03:54.003 --> 04:00.914
to. Well, we... What were you looking for? Well, 
the first problem that jumped up, the Midwestern

04:07.926 --> 04:21.107
states started raising sound about us having 
those Brazilian bulls down here. You're talking

04:22.859 --> 04:25.582
about the U.S. Livestock Sanitary Commission. 
Well, those people were all members of the U.S.

04:25.602 --> 04:34.692
Sanitary Commission, U.S. Livestock Sanitary. 
But they had a little organization of their own

04:34.712 --> 04:49.508
group up there in the Midwest, in Kansas and 
Nebraska and one or two other states. And they were

04:50.551 --> 04:52.834
going to have a meeting up there about this. So I got 
on an

04:53.275 --> 05:03.290
airplane and flew up there. And they were going to 
quarantine. They were going to embargo against

05:06.474 --> 05:08.397
Texas. Well, I told them what had happened and how I 
felt about it and how we were keeping them under

05:08.938 --> 05:16.870
observation. They said, well, that's all right. 
That's all right. We think you've got the thing

05:20.291 --> 05:21.853
under control. So I come on back home. Wasn't a week 
later that the Florida people started. We're

05:28.143 --> 05:30.107
going to embargo against Texas cattle. They've 
got those Brazilian bulls over there. I jump on an

05:32.771 --> 05:42.647
airplane and fly down to Lake Okeechobee and went 
into that little old hotel down there and heard a

05:32.771 --> 05:42.647
couple of fellas talking and Yeah, there's a whole 
delegation of those so-and-sos coming over here,

05:43.522 --> 05:47.767
but we're going to quarantine their cattle. Man, I 
didn't sleep very good that night. I thought,

05:49.650 --> 05:51.532
well, I'm that delegation. We got up the next 
morning and went down to this meeting of the

05:52.353 --> 05:56.878
commission. They were meeting at the courthouse 
there. And they were discussing a little fever

05:59.922 --> 06:06.650
tick outbreak that they had down there, you know, 
coming out of the Everglades. I don't know whether

06:06.670 --> 06:12.077
they still got them or not, but every so often those 
deer and whatnot will come out of the Everglades

06:12.310 --> 06:40.157
and bring those old fever ticks and they have to 
fight them back you know and they were talking

06:12.310 --> 06:40.157
about how they were handling that situation and I 
said I see they came to me and I got up and I said well I

06:12.310 --> 06:40.157
see you this fever tick situation over you people 
have got problems over here too but I said we're not

06:12.310 --> 06:40.157
worried in Texas we we feel like you'll take care of 
it all right and then I went into details of what we

06:40.424 --> 07:04.474
had done and what we had and how we were handling it 
and they said well we think that's all right we

06:40.424 --> 07:04.474
think you can handle your your problems in Texas 
too so we broke up here comes an old boy running down

06:40.424 --> 07:04.474
there and said shook hands with me and says boy you 
sure did a good job I said what do you mean he says

06:40.424 --> 07:04.474
getting this thing straightened out said you know 
If we'd have got that embargo against you, we'd

07:07.222 --> 07:12.969
have sure had a good sale of brame of bulls here in 
Florida. He was just laughing about it. So a lot of

07:15.372 --> 07:20.999
those things, a lot of those embargoes are just 
economic things, see, for economic reasons. But

07:21.059 --> 07:36.098
the livestock, I got the general impression that 
all the, that

07:21.059 --> 07:36.098
the Livestock Sanitary Commission didn't 
necessarily promulgate their rules on the basis

07:21.059 --> 07:36.098
of good veterinary medicine and quarantines and

07:36.348 --> 07:52.955
from the basis of good practice in the shipment of 
cattle, but they were merely there to kind of help

07:36.348 --> 07:52.955
keep the rest of the country off the Texas bag. Is 
that right? Oh, I see your point. That's exactly

07:56.742 --> 07:58.004
right. That's exactly right. And people... You 
know, we had some good feeder cattle down here. We

08:04.613 --> 08:18.774
export a lot more cattle than we use, and we have to 
constantly be on guard to keep somebody from

08:04.613 --> 08:18.774
quarantining against us. Oh, yeah, yeah. And a lot 
of your regulatory laws are simply economic

08:20.296 --> 08:28.528
embargo-type things, you know. The Livestock 
Sanitary Commission was more in Oregon at that

08:28.745 --> 08:41.745
